  <div class="friendReviews elementListBrown" >
    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_2928596975" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2928596975" />
    <a title="Ryan Schmitt" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/4819365-ryan-schmitt"><img alt="Ryan Schmitt" src="https://s.gr-assets.com/assets/nophoto/user/m_50x66-82093808bca726cb3249a493fbd3bd0f.png" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2928596975?book_show_action=true">Sep 05, 2019</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Ryan Schmitt" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Ryan Schmitt" href="/user/show/4819365-ryan-schmitt">Ryan Schmitt</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Hardcover " href="/book/show/29570508-the-nightmare-years-1930-40">review of another edition</a>


        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2928596975" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer9331766357078004883">I came across a used copy of this book in Powell&apos;s (hardcover, no dust jacket, three bucks). I had previously read the author&apos;s <a href='https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/767171.The_Rise_and_Fall_of_the_Third_Reich_A_History_of_Nazi_Germany' title='The Rise and Fall of the Third Reich A History of Nazi Germany by William L. Shirer' rel='nofollow noopener'>The Rise and Fall of the Third Reich: A History of Nazi Germany</a>. Whereas that book was primarily based on primary sources (the mountainous Nazi archives captured by the Allies as the war was ending), this memoir is based primarily on the author&apos;s personal experience watching the Nazi saga unfold in real time as a German-, French-, Italian-, and Spanish-speaking foreign </span>
  <span id="freeText9331766357078004883" style="display:none">I came across a used copy of this book in Powell's (hardcover, no dust jacket, three bucks). I had previously read the author's <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/767171.The_Rise_and_Fall_of_the_Third_Reich_A_History_of_Nazi_Germany" title="The Rise and Fall of the Third Reich A History of Nazi Germany by William L. Shirer" rel="nofollow noopener">The Rise and Fall of the Third Reich: A History of Nazi Germany</a>. Whereas that book was primarily based on primary sources (the mountainous Nazi archives captured by the Allies as the war was ending), this memoir is based primarily on the author's personal experience watching the Nazi saga unfold in real time as a German-, French-, Italian-, and Spanish-speaking foreign correspondent. The book contains the type of fascinating detail you can only get from someone who had actually been there, such as this (p. 127):<br /><br /><blockquote><br />It was the eyes that dominated [Hitler's] otherwise common face. They were hypnotic. Piercing. Penetrating. As far as I could tell, they were light blue, but the color was not the thing you noticed. What hit you at once was their power. They stared at you. They stared through you. [...] All through the days at Nuremberg I would observe hardened old party leaders, who had spent years in the company of Hitler, freeze as he paused to talk to one or the other of them, hypnotized by his penetrating glare. [...] Martha Dodd, the vivacious young daughter of the American ambassador, had told me a day or two before I left for Nuremberg, to watch out for Hitler's eyes. "They are unforgettable," she said. "They overwhelm you."<br /></blockquote><br /><br />Admittedly, the middle section of the book often feels like a rehash of the material from Rise and Fall, with occasional anecdotes interspersed about travel, family life, and what it was like to work in the Great Early Days of News Radio under a regime of censorship which eventually grew intolerable. However, the book reaches its climax during the Battle of France, as the author follows the German Sixth Army from Aachen all the way to Paris, describing what he encounters along the way. Other significant plot points include the RAF's first bombing of Berlin, the failure of Operation Sea Lion, and the author's flight from Germany, including the smuggling of his massive <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/23756.Berlin_Diary_The_Journal_of_a_Foreign_Correspondent_1934_1941" title="Berlin Diary The Journal of a Foreign Correspondent 1934-1941 by William L. Shirer" rel="nofollow noopener">Berlin Diary: The Journal of a Foreign Correspondent 1934-1941</a>, whose contents, if discovered, easily could have gotten him beheaded.<br /><br />Readers of "Rise and Fall" will recognize many of Shirer's same tics: he has to frequently mention that everyone is an idiot except for himself and Winston Churchill, that the French have gone stupid and crazy, that a high-ranking Nazi or German general is (pick one: bemedaled, monocled, pig-eyed, corpulent, mediocre, dense, pretentious), and that the German people are uniquely war-like, dishonorable, and disgusting. This does get tiresome after hundreds and hundreds of pages, but it's far from unendurable.</span>
  <a data-text-id="9331766357078004883" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

