<div id="review_3633916420" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3633916420" />
    <a title="Phil Gavenda" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/56990774-phil-gavenda"><img alt="Phil Gavenda" src="https://s.gr-assets.com/assets/nophoto/user/m_50x66-82093808bca726cb3249a493fbd3bd0f.png" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3633916420?book_show_action=true">Dec 27, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Phil Gavenda" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Phil Gavenda" href="/user/show/56990774-phil-gavenda">Phil Gavenda</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9780316787031" href="/book/show/693567.The_Nightmare_Years">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/56990774-phil-gavenda?shelf=history">history</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3633916420" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer1319450963042890084"><p>I&apos;ve had this on my shelf for over thirty years but just now read it. I found it an enjoyable and informative read. The author was an American journalist who spent most of his early years overseas; this book is one of his autobiographical trilogy <i>20th Century Journey</i> covering 1930-1940, most of which he spent in Nazi Germany. (His best known work is probably <i>Rise and Fall of the Third Reich</i>.) For me, it dragged a bit early on, as it follows him from India, thence through the Middle East on his s</p></span>
  <span id="freeText1319450963042890084" style="display:none"><p>I've had this on my shelf for over thirty years but just now read it. I found it an enjoyable and informative read. The author was an American journalist who spent most of his early years overseas; this book is one of his autobiographical trilogy <i>20th Century Journey</i> covering 1930-1940, most of which he spent in Nazi Germany. (His best known work is probably <i>Rise and Fall of the Third Reich</i>.) For me, it dragged a bit early on, as it follows him from India, thence through the Middle East on his slow return trip to the West. As the early year of his work coincide with the nadir of the Depression, much time is spent with his search for steady work. </p><br /><p>I found most interesting the period starting with his time in Paris, the fall of the Republic, the rise of fascism not only in Paris but throughout Europe, then his time in Berlin, where he was close to the 'action' and a first-hand observer alongside (literally) Hitler as he took over the government and also had a ringside seat at the subjugation of Czechoslovakia, Austria, Poland, Belgium and France. There are striking similarities with our own time; notably the rise of the fascists in France as well as in Germany, and the willingness of Germans to cede their own democracy to the Nazis. Shirer often asks the question: What could these otherwise decent people be <i>thinking??</i></p><br /><a class="jsShowSpoiler spoilerAction">(view spoiler)</a><span class="spoilerContainer" style="display: none">[He finally left Germany as he feared the censors, SS, and Hilter himself were applying pressure to stifle his reportage and he'd heard rumors he was going to be arrested for spying. <a class="jsHideSpoiler spoilerAction">(hide spoiler)</a>]</span><br />I found the writing quite readable and well-researched; often supplementing his own diary notes with secondary sources from years later.</span>
  <a data-text-id="1319450963042890084" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


