<span id="freeTextContainer17524063662077930427">Wow....you have to have a story to tell in a 600 page book and Shirer certainly does. And in an extremely interesting journalistic style. He has wonderful takes on the characters in the Third Reich from Hitler to Goering to Himmler and lesser personages as well as some Brits and Frenchmen (I came to dislike Neville Chamberlin for his groveling ways). The mistakes (on both sides) that led to death and destruction were appalling. And most chilling of all the Nazi use of propaganda through Goebbels</span>
  <span id="freeText17524063662077930427" style="display:none">Wow....you have to have a story to tell in a 600 page book and Shirer certainly does. And in an extremely interesting journalistic style. He has wonderful takes on the characters in the Third Reich from Hitler to Goering to Himmler and lesser personages as well as some Brits and Frenchmen (I came to dislike Neville Chamberlin for his groveling ways). The mistakes (on both sides) that led to death and destruction were appalling. And most chilling of all the Nazi use of propaganda through Goebbels but the Master of Lying was Hitler. He sold the German people through lies, deceptions and spin and blamed it all on the Jews.....or the Slavs.....or the Brits who bombed hospitals vs the Luftwaffe who never bombed anything but strategic military sites (tell that to a Londoner!) Scarily he reminded me many times of what the past four years exposed in us of media, truth telling and responsibility. <br /></span>
