  <span id="freeText881546493420136631" style="display:none">I just love the style of writing. You feel you are sat next to him as he tells his story. This book is for the Shirer connaisseur. If you want a history of the second world war then go to his monumental work on the Third Reich. However if you want an account of the early years of WWII written by someone who was right there next to the action as if in a film, and who writes in such a way that you feel it is all unfolding in front of your eyes then this is the book.<br /><br />My heighlight is his description and wonderment at how quickly the French 3rd Republic caved in to the initial onslaughts. How did so powerful a nation lose its will and ability to control events. This has made me order the Shirer book on the Third Republic. Very much looking forward to learning more.</span>
