  <span id="freeText13140033913161462829" style="display:none">Edward R. Murrow gets all or most of the attention regarding reporting of what was happening in Europe during WWII. However, William Shirer was actually in Germany, while Murrow reported from the safe confines of England. Shire watched as the Nazis rose to power and was acquainted with several prominent party members. Shire and a handful of war correspondents reported the horrors they were witnessing only to see their reports sanitized by the American media. Shire and company were eventually kicked out of Germany for being too candid. This book reads like a novel; much easier reading than The Rise and Fall of the Third Reich, the book for which Shirer is best known.</span>
