<div id="review_3920014080" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3920014080" />
    <a title="Michael Young" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/115585496-michael-young"><img alt="Michael Young" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1611787742p2/115585496.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3920014080?book_show_action=true">Apr 21, 2021</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Michael Young" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Michael Young" href="/user/show/115585496-michael-young">Michael Young</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3920014080" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer440657111851655246">Shirer is an excellent writer. This is the 2nd book of his I&apos;ve read (the other being Rise and Fall of the Third Reich), and both books I couldn&apos;t put down. Not only because of the contents, which are his personal experience of Nazi Germany coupled with the Secret Nazi Documents, but his ability to keep the reader captive. Most books I have to get used to the writer&apos;s style before it starts reading with fluidity. But with Shirer, it&apos;s automatic from page one. <br/><br/>If you&apos;re a history buff, a student,</span>
  <span id="freeText440657111851655246" style="display:none">Shirer is an excellent writer. This is the 2nd book of his I've read (the other being Rise and Fall of the Third Reich), and both books I couldn't put down. Not only because of the contents, which are his personal experience of Nazi Germany coupled with the Secret Nazi Documents, but his ability to keep the reader captive. Most books I have to get used to the writer's style before it starts reading with fluidity. But with Shirer, it's automatic from page one. <br /><br />If you're a history buff, a student, or just an avid reader, this book will fill your appetite. <br /><br />I got this at a thrift book store, so I wasn't aware it was vol. 2 of 3. I will definitely be looking for the first and third volumes.</span>
  <a data-text-id="440657111851655246" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

